<td>
<hr>
<div class='commentinfo comment_'>
2003-09-23 00:19:47 (3903 days ago)
<div id='contact-346'><span class='name'>Brad Roberts</span><span class='send-message'><a href="/content/Contact/view/contactid/346/display/detail/">Details</a></span></div> </div>
<div class='commentbox'>
<br/>
<br/>
The Linville by Chris Young<br/>
<br/>
&quot;If its not the best run that you've ever done, I'll drive shuttle for the next year&quot;<br/>
That was a promise I made to a friend who doesn't like long days on the river. The Linville River,<br/>
which runs through Linville Gorge in Western North Carolina, is where I initially made this vow.<br/>
Linville is the East's version of expedition boating. The run is 16+ miles long and has around 12<br/>
miles of non-stop class 5 action. In 1989 the American Whitewater journal listed &quot;the top ten hair<br/>
runs in the east&quot; with such other runs as the Lower Meadow and the Big Sandy. Some 15 years later<br/>
Linville hasn't given up that title. It was generally descended in two days until the mid 90's.<br/>
<br/>
The river begins at the base of a huge waterfall, the famous and scenic Linville Falls, and had a<br/>
couple miles paddle in before the onslaught. Once the rapids begin you will run or portage such<br/>
classic drops as Babel Tower, Drunk Tank, Twiggy aka Homey's slot, Cave, and Cathedral Falls.<br/>
Though, the run is not only a few big rapids, it is non-stop dangerous class 5 drops, one after<br/>
another for about 12 miles. There are more than enough stories about heinous swims, boats that are<br/>
gone forever down drainpipe sieves, and other troubles by some of the best boaters in the<br/>
country.<br/>
<br/>
Of course with any run of this nature there are many tales. Has someone run the bottom of Linville<br/>
Falls? Has someone run the whole run in one day with no portages? There are two horrible sieve<br/>
rapids thataare4 thought to be mandatory portages, although some beg to differ. It seems like no<br/>
one can agree. One thing is for sure, when we got off the river that day my smiling friend told me<br/>
I didn't have to drive.<br/>
<br/>
Reprinted with permission from LVM. </div>
</td>
</tr>
